# Activity A(ii) — The Proposal (Most Important Part)

This is where **most marks come from**.

You must design a **digital solution idea** and explain it.

Your proposal must include:

---

# 1. Business Context

Explain **the company and the problem**.

Example:

GibJohn Tutoring currently offers:

- face-to-face lessons
- learning resources
- academic support

However they want a **digital platform** to:

- expand learning
- monitor progress
- allow interactive learning

So your solution must solve this.

---

# 2. Description of the Proposed Solution

Explain the **system you will build**.

Example solution:

A **web-based learning platform**.

Features:

Student features

- login
- view lessons
- take quizzes
- track progress
- earn rewards

Tutor features

- upload resources
- monitor student performance
- create quizzes

Admin features

- manage users
- schedule lessons
- manage rewards

---

# 3. Functional Requirements

These describe **what the system must do**.

Examples:

- users can **register accounts**
- students can **access learning materials**
- tutors can **upload content**
- system can **track progress**
- system can **generate quizzes**
- reward points are given for completion

---

# 4. Non-Functional Requirements

These describe **how well the system works**.

Examples:

Performance

- pages load in under 2 seconds

Security

- encrypted login

Accessibility

- adjustable text size
- screen reader compatibility

Compatibility

- works on phones, tablets, and PCs

---

# 5. Decomposition of the Problem

Break the system into **smaller problems**.

Example:

Main system:

Learning Platform

Sub systems:

1️⃣ User management
2️⃣ Learning content system
3️⃣ Assessment system
4️⃣ Progress tracking
5️⃣ Reward system

Each has smaller processes.

Example:

User Management

- registration
- login
- password reset
- role assignment

The mark scheme specifically expects **problem decomposition**.

---

# 6. KPIs (Key Performance Indicators)

These measure **system success**.

Examples:

- 90% of students complete quizzes
- 80% user satisfaction
- 1000 active users within 6 months
- system uptime 99%

---

# 7. User Acceptance Criteria

These define **what must work before the client accepts the system**.

Examples:

- student can log in
- student can complete quizzes
- tutor can upload lessons
- progress tracking displays correctly

---

# 8. Risks + Mitigation

The mark scheme expects **security risks**.

Examples:

### SQL Injection

Risk:
Hackers accessing database

Solution:

- input sanitisation
- prepared SQL statements

---

### Cross Site Scripting (XSS)

Risk:
Malicious scripts in forms

Solution:

- input validation
- escaping output

---

### Man-in-the-Middle attack

Risk:
Data interception

Solution:

- HTTPS
- SSL encryption

---

# 9. Legal and Ethical Considerations

Important in education systems.

Examples:

**GDPR**

- student data must be protected
- parental consent if under 18

**Copyright**

- learning materials must not be illegally copied

**Accessibility**

- comply with WCAG




## 1. Overview of the Proposed System

The proposed solution is a **Retail Management System** designed to manage product sales, stock levels, supplier coordination and customer purchases.

The system will allow:

- Customers to create accounts and purchase products
- Admin staff to monitor business performance
- Staff to track supplier deliveries
- Suppliers to view restock requests
- Customers to receive loyalty rewards

The system will operate as a **web-based platform** accessible on both **desktop and mobile devices**, ensuring flexibility for customers and staff.

The system will consist of two main parts:

- **Frontend (GUI)** – user interface for customers, staff, suppliers and admin
- **Backend** – server-side logic handling authentication, stock management and data processing.

---

## 2. Target Users

### Customers

Customers will use the system to:

- create accounts
- browse products
- purchase items
- track loyalty rewards
- view purchase history

### Staff

Staff will use the system to:

- monitor stock levels
- track supplier deliveries
- receive stock updates
- identify items needing restocking

### Admin

Admins will access a dashboard containing:

- sales analytics
- stock levels
- product availability
- expiry monitoring
- supplier data

### Suppliers

Suppliers will access restocking information including:

- items requiring restocking
- order quantities
- delivery status
- shipment tracking

---

## 3. Key System Features

### Customer Account System

Customers can:

- create accounts
- log in securely
- manage personal details
- access loyalty rewards

Passwords will be securely stored using **hashed encryption**.

---

### Product Catalogue

The system will store all products with:

- product name
- price
- stock quantity
- expiry date
- availability status

Customers can search and filter products before purchasing.

---

### Checkout & Payment System

Customers can:

- add products to a basket
- review total cost
- complete purchases at checkout

The system will automatically:

- verify stock availability
- calculate total price
- update inventory after purchase

---

### Loyalty Reward System

Customers earn **loyalty points** after purchases.

Points can later be used for:

- discounts
- rewards
- promotional offers

This feature helps **retain customers and encourage repeat purchases**.

---

### Stock Management

The system will continuously track stock levels.

Features include:

- real-time stock monitoring
- automatic restock alerts
- expiry date tracking
- unavailable product detection

---

### Supplier Integration

Suppliers will receive notifications when stock reaches a **restocking threshold**.

They can:

- confirm restock orders
- update shipment progress
- provide delivery tracking information

Staff can track delivery progress to estimate **restocking arrival times**.

---

### Admin Dashboard

Admins will have access to a central dashboard displaying:

- sales performance
- stock growth trends
- items close to expiry
- product availability
- supplier activity

This helps support **business decision-making and inventory planning**.

---

## 4. Accessibility Features

The system will support a wide range of accessibility features including:

- adjustable text sizes
- high contrast colour mode
- screen reader compatibility
- keyboard navigation
- mobile responsive design

These features ensure the system is usable by a wide range of customers.

---

## 5. System Benefits

The proposed system provides several benefits for the retail company.

### Improved stock control

Automatic stock tracking helps reduce:

- overstocking
- stock shortages
- expired product sales

### Improved customer experience

Customers can easily browse and purchase products while earning loyalty rewards.

### Better supplier coordination

Suppliers receive automated restocking information, improving delivery efficiency.

### Business insights

The admin dashboard allows the company to monitor sales performance and product demand.
